Layer 1 — Data Sources
This is where everything begins. 
Four types of raw data enter the system — patient records from past visits, 
doctor questions typed in plain English, 
live readings from ICU machines like heartbeat and temperature,
and hospital operational data like bed counts and department costs.

Layer 2 — Ingestion
This layer picks up the data from each source and brings it into the system. Batch ETL collects patient records in bulk, the web portal receives doctor questions, MQTT continuously pulls live ICU readings, and CSV uploads bring in the operational data.

Layer 3 — Staging
Think of this as a waiting room. All the raw data that just arrived is held here temporarily without any changes. Nothing is processed or modified yet — it is just stored safely before the next step begins.

Layer 4 — Data Cleaning
Now the data gets fixed and prepared. Duplicate entries are removed, missing values are filled or flagged, dates are put into the same format, inconsistent spellings are corrected, and everything is checked to make sure it is valid. Only clean and correct data is allowed to move forward.

Layer 5 — Storage
Clean data is now saved into the right database. Patient records go into the SQL database, doctor query history goes into the Vector DB for smart searching, ICU vitals go into the Time-series database, and hospital operational data goes into the Data Warehouse.

Layer 6 — AI and Analytics Layer
This is where the intelligence happens. The ML model predicts which patients are at risk of being readmitted. The LLM reads the Vector DB and answers the doctor's question in plain English. The alerting engine watches live vitals and sends a warning if something looks dangerous. The BI engine reads the Data Warehouse and builds the monthly management report.

Layer 7 — Output
The final results reach the right person. The doctor sees risk alerts and readmission flags on their dashboard. The doctor also gets a plain English answer to their query. The nurse gets an immediate notification if a patient's vitals cross a dangerous threshold. Management receives a monthly report showing costs and bed usage.